# Naming Conventions

> **For non-engineers:** Names help humans and AI understand what code does. This rule defines how we name things so everyone stays consistent.

---

## Quick Reference

| What you're naming | Style | Example |
|--------------------|-------|---------|
| HTML element IDs | camelCase | `uploadArea`, `topText` |
| HTML class names | kebab-case | `upload-area`, `control-group` |
| CSS selectors | kebab-case | `.upload-area`, `#uploadArea` |
| JavaScript variables & functions | camelCase | `sourceImage`, `loadImage()` |
| Constants (never change) | UPPER_SNAKE | `CANVAS_SIZE`, `DEFAULT_FONT` |
| File names | kebab-case | `styles.css`, `app.js` |

---

## HTML

### IDs (unique identifiers)

**Rule:** Use **camelCase** — lowercase first word, capitalize each following word.

**Why:** IDs are used in JavaScript. camelCase matches JavaScript conventions.

```
✅ Good:  id="uploadArea"   id="topText"   id="downloadBtn"
❌ Avoid: id="upload_area"  id="top-text"  id="DownloadBtn"
```

### Class names

**Rule:** Use **kebab-case** — all lowercase, words separated by hyphens.

**Why:** Classes describe what something is (e.g. "upload area"). Hyphens read like spaces and are standard in CSS.

```
✅ Good:  class="upload-area"   class="control-group"   class="canvas-container"
❌ Avoid: class="uploadArea"   class="control_group"   class="CanvasContainer"
```

---

## CSS

**Rule:** Match the HTML. Classes use **kebab-case**; IDs use **camelCase**.

```
✅ Good:
.upload-area { }
.control-group span { }
#uploadArea { }
#downloadBtn:hover { }

❌ Avoid:
.uploadArea { }      /* class should be kebab-case */
#upload-area { }     /* ID should match HTML (camelCase) */
```

---

## JavaScript

### Variables and functions

**Rule:** Use **camelCase** — lowercase first word, capitalize each following word.

**Why:** This is the standard for JavaScript. Easy to read and type.

```
✅ Good:
const sourceImage = null;
function loadImage(file) { }
function fitImageToCanvas() { }
const topTextInput = document.getElementById('topText');

❌ Avoid:
const source_image = null;   /* snake_case */
function LoadImage() { }     /* PascalCase is for classes */
```

### Constants (values that never change)

**Rule:** Use **UPPER_SNAKE_CASE** — all caps, words separated by underscores.

**Why:** Instantly signals "this value is fixed" and helps avoid accidental changes.

```
✅ Good:
const CANVAS_SIZE = 600;
const DEFAULT_FONT = 'impact, sans-serif';

❌ Avoid:
const canvasSize = 600;      /* looks like a normal variable */
const default_font = '...';   /* lowercase doesn't stand out */
```

### Names should describe purpose

**Rule:** Use clear, descriptive names. Avoid abbreviations unless very common.

```
✅ Good:
uploadArea, topTextInput, fontSizeValue, downloadMeme
```

```
❌ Avoid:
ua, tt, fs, dl  (too short, unclear)
```

---

## Files

**Rule:** Use **kebab-case** for file names.

**Why:** Works well across operating systems, URLs, and tools. Avoids case-sensitivity issues.

```
✅ Good:  styles.css, app.js, meme-generator.js
❌ Avoid: Styles.css, App.js, memeGenerator.js
```

---

## Best Practices Summary

1. **Be consistent** — Same type of thing, same style.
2. **Be descriptive** — `uploadArea` beats `area`; `loadImage` beats `load`.
3. **Match the language** — HTML/CSS: kebab-case for classes. JavaScript: camelCase.
4. **Keep IDs unique** — One ID per page; use classes for repeated styling.
5. **Avoid abbreviations** — `fontSize` is clearer than `fs` unless the abbreviation is universal (e.g. `id`, `url`).
